<p>The latest in a long line of instruments using correlation
spectroscopy to remotely sense the atmosphere is the Measurement of
Pollution In The Troposphere (<a
href="http://www.atmosp.physics.utoronto.ca/MOPITT/home.html">MOPITT</a>)
instrument launched on <a href="http://terra.nasa.gov/">TERRA</a> in
1999. The satellite Terra is the flagship of NASA's Earth Observing
System (EOS) programme. Subsystems comprising a pressure modulator
cell, a molecular sieve and position pickoff (PPO) electronics were
supplied to the instrument integrators by Oxford University, and in
collaboration with the Rutherford Appleton Laboratory (<a
href="http://www.cclrc.ac.uk/">RAL</a>) who supplied the sieves. A
finished MOPITT PMC is shown in Fig 3.</p>

<p>The technique of correlation spectroscopy is not limited solely to the
study of terrestrial atmospheres and pressure modulator radiometers
have been flown on a number of planetary missions. To date these
include the Venus Orbiter Radiometric Temperature sounder EXperiment
(VORTEX) on Venus Explorer, the Pressure Modulator Infra-Red
Radiometer (PMIRR-1) on Mars Observer and PMIRR-2 on Mars Climate
Orbiter.  Unfortunately, both Mars spacecraft were lost, but the Venus
experiment was successful. A spin-off from the pressure modulator
technology was the use of similar devices to drive <a
href="mechanical_coolers.html">Stirling cycle coolers</a> for the
detectors in ISAMS, ATSR, MOPITT and HIRDLS.</p>

